Margarida Cunha, director of the ngun Mbak Kutem community health center in Kandal province near Phnom Penh, says ‘Malnutrition in children of separated families is common. Often, whatever few resources are available to the family go to support the man, leaving children without the much-needed care.’

The deepest wounds are inflicted upon the children and women, who lose out on any support from their husbands during times of hardship, with malnutrition and starvation afflicting mothers and their children.

As the NGO, Aide a l’Enfance Malee (AME) points out, many such poor households have become dependent, both economically and emotionally, on their fathers. So when the man is ousted, the breakdown of the family can lead to conditions of poverty and malnutrition to linger for years. The example is given of the woman living alongside her grandparents and grandchildren in the Stung Meanchey garbage dump, like many women as described above, not included in the household, to also having psychological burdens due to the estranged relationship with her children and her husband.
